```
int faceRecMan::landMark(IplImage* img,std::vector<Rect>faces,std::vector<Point> &points)
{
    int i;
    std::vector<full_object_detection> shapes;
    cv_image<uchar> cimg(img);
    time_record();
    dlib::rectangle iRect;
    for (i = 0; i < faces.size(); i++){
        iRect.set_left(faces[i].x);
        iRect.set_top(faces[i].y);
        iRect.set_right(faces[i].x+faces[i].width);
        iRect.set_bottom(faces[i].y+faces[i].height);
        shapes.push_back(m_pose_model(cimg,iRect));
    }
    for(i=0 ; i < shapes[0].num_parts(); i++){
        Point pt;
        pt.x = (int)shapes[0].part(i).x();
        pt.y = (int)shapes[0].part(i).y();
        points.push_back(pt);
    }
    time_report("lm");
    return 0;
}
```

@jaraco it isn't the keyring password that I am concerned about, but instead something stored in the keyring.

As an example, say I process pdf files on the command line.  Sometimes they have passwords.  When I encounter one, I ask the user for the pdf password, and use keyring to remember it.  However I don't want keyring to remember that password forever, only an hour or so.  I can't make the script go and clear out the password an hour later since it won't be running. 

I can't tell how the desktop environments implement the choice of remembering passwords for no time, for a set period of time, for the session or indefinitely.  But they use keyrings and hence the functionality exists, and I was hoping that python-keyring could expose it.

